TITLE: Lazy Route Loading - React Router (JSX)
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to use the `lazy` property in React Router to enable code-splitting for routes.  The `lazy` property accepts an async function (typically a dynamic import) that resolves the route's non-route-matching properties (`loader`, `action`, `element`/`Component`, `errorElement`/`ErrorBoundary`, `shouldRevalidate`, `handle`). This allows for on-demand loading of route modules, improving initial load time.
SOURCE: https://github.com/remix-run/react-router/blob/main/packages/react-router/CHANGELOG.md#_snippet_34

LANGUAGE: jsx
CODE:
```
// In this example, we assume most folks land on the homepage so we include that
// in our critical-path bundle, but then we lazily load modules for /a and /b so
// they don't load until the user navigates to those routes
let routes = createRoutesFromElements(
  <Route path="/" element={<Layout />}>
    <Route index element={<Home />} />
    <Route path="a" lazy={() => import("./a")} />
    <Route path="b" lazy={() => import("./b")} />
  </Route>
);

```

